result.execSummary: Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Rzell J Groce in court with attorney Nathan Opland-Dobs.  Defendant Rzell J Groce in custody.  Deann L. Heard appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Parties are in receipt of the doctor's report; neither side contends its findings.  Court has colloquy with defendant as to whether or not he believes he is competent.  Defendant advised the court that he does not believe he is competent to assist his lawyer in these proceedings.  Court finds defendant incompetent at this time, but likely to regain with proper treatment and ordered him committed to the Wisconsin Department of Health Services.  Case remains suspended; defendant given credit for 55 days.  Court ordered defendant remanded to the Sheriff's Department for transport to institution.
